segment.source: Input profiles (or input locales) describe the language of the input entered, and the keyboard on which it is being entered.
segment.target: Input profiles (or input locales) describe the language of the input entered, and the keyboard on which it is being entered.

segment.source: Input profiles (or input locales) describe the language of the input entered, and the keyboard on which it is being entered.
segment.target: Input profiles (or input locales) describe the language of the input entered, and the keyboard on which it is being entered.

segment.source: When the first user logs into Windows and identifies their region, Windows sets the input profiles.
segment.target: When the first user logs into Windows and identifies their region, Windows sets the input profiles.

segment.source: The input profiles are made up of a language identifier and a keyboard identifier.
segment.target: The input profiles are made up of a language identifier and a keyboard identifier.

segment.source: For example, the Arabic (Algerian) input profile is 1401:00020401, where 1401 is the hexadecimal identifier of the language: Arabic (Algeria) and 00020401 is the hexadecimal identifier of the keyboard: Arabic 101.
segment.target: For example, the Arabic (Algerian) input profile is 1401:00020401, where 1401 is the hexadecimal identifier of the language: Arabic (Algeria) and 00020401 is the hexadecimal identifier of the keyboard: Arabic 101.

segment.source: When the user first identifies the time and date format (User Locale) as Algeria, Windows sets up both the primary input profile, and a secondary input profile: French (France) with French keyboard.
segment.target: When the user first identifies the time and date format (User Locale) as Algeria, Windows sets up both the primary input profile, and a secondary input profile: French (France) with French keyboard.

segment.source: The secondary input profile can help the user by providing a keyboard with a Latin character set for tasks that require it, such as filling out email addresses.
segment.target: The secondary input profile can help the user by providing a keyboard with a Latin character set for tasks that require it, such as filling out email addresses.

segment.source: Some character sets (like CHS IME) have a Latin character set built in.
segment.target: Some character sets (like CHS IME) have a Latin character set built in.

segment.source: Windows uses the language component of the input profile for tasks like spelling, hyphenation, and text prediction of the intended key press when using the touch-screen keyboard.
segment.target: Windows uses the language component of the input profile for tasks like spelling, hyphenation, and text prediction of the intended key press when using the touch-screen keyboard.

segment.source: When setting up new devices for your users, you can use the DISM commands: /Set-InputLocale or /Set-AllIntl to identify a default input profile.
segment.target: When setting up new devices for your users, you can use the DISM commands: /Set-InputLocale or /Set-AllIntl to identify a default input profile.

segment.source: You can either select the input profile by its language and keyboard pair (1401:00020401) or you can use a languageregion tag to receive the default settings for that language/region.
segment.target: You can either select the input profile by its language and keyboard pair (1401:00020401) or you can use a languageregion tag to receive the default settings for that language/region.

segment.source: For a list of language/culture names, see Available Language Packs for Windows.
segment.target: For a list of language/culture names, see Available Language Packs for Windows.
